# All sensitive values arrive via op run TF_VAR_ injection - never fill them here.
#
# GOL-385: this file used to ship placeholder values that silently produced a
# DIFFERENT droplet than the one live in prod. `healthchecks_ping_url` feeds the
# blogs droplet's user_data, and the DO provider stores user_data as a SHA1 --
# so a wrong value here does not surface as "backup ping misconfigured", it
# surfaces as `digitalocean_droplet.blogs must be replaced` with an opaque
# (sensitive value) diff and no hint as to which input moved.
#
# Everything that CAN be defaulted now is, in variables.tf (admin_ip_cidr,
# region, blogs_droplet_size, droplet_image, image tags). Prod's SSH rule and
# sizing are therefore reproducible from code alone. Do not re-add them here:
# a stale copy in a gitignored tfvars silently overrides the codified value,
# which is the exact class of failure GOL-385 is about. (The old example's
# admin_ip_cidr was 203.0.113.7/32 -- a TEST-NET-3 documentation address --
# so copying it verbatim also locked SSH to an IP nobody owns.)
#
# That leaves TWO inputs a plan/apply needs, and NEITHER belongs in this file:
#
#   healthchecks_ping_url   -> op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/Grove Infra/healthchecks_ping_url
#                              "" disables backup pings. Wire via .env.op.
#   grove_revalidate_secret -> op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/Grove Infra/grove_revalidate_secret
#                              >=32 chars. Deliberately has NO default so a bare
#                              apply cannot ship a placeholder secret to prod;
#                              the cost is that `plan` FAILS until it is set.
#                              That is intentional - supply it via .env.op.
#
# So in the healthy state this file is EMPTY of real values. If you find
# yourself filling it in, the value is missing from 1Password -- fix it there,
# or prod stops being reproducible the moment your laptop is not the machine
# running the apply.
